                    <MudText Typo="Typo.h6" Class="mb-2">üîê How Your Data is Protected</MudText>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-2">1. Client-Side Processing (Zero Server Trust)</MudText>
                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-3">
                        Stitch is a <strong>100% client-side application</strong>. All text processing, encryption, file parsing, and audio generation happens
                        in your browser using WebAssembly. Your text and files <strong>never touch our servers</strong> - because we don't have any servers!
                        The only external calls are directly to the TTS provider APIs you choose.
                    </MudText>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-2">2. AES-256-GCM Encryption for API Keys</MudText>
                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-3">
                        Your API keys are encrypted using <strong>AES-256-GCM</strong> (Advanced Encryption Standard with Galois/Counter Mode) - the same
                        encryption standard used by governments and banks. Your master password is never stored anywhere - it's used to derive an encryption
                        key via <strong>PBKDF2</strong> with 100,000 iterations, making brute-force attacks computationally infeasible.
                    </MudText>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-2">3. Local Storage Only</MudText>
                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-3">
                        All data is stored in your browser's local storage (for settings) and IndexedDB (for models). This data is sandboxed per-origin
                        and cannot be accessed by other websites. Clearing your browser data will remove all stored information.
                    </MudText>

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.subtitle2" Class="mb-2">4. No Tracking, No Analytics, No Telemetry</MudText>
                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-4">
                        Stitch does <strong>not collect any usage data</strong>. There are no analytics scripts, no error reporting services, no tracking pixels.
                        We genuinely have no idea how you use the app, what text you synthesize, or which providers you prefer - and that's by design.
                    </MudText>

                    <MudDivider Class="my-4" />

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.h6" Class="mb-2">üõ°Ô∏è Security Best Practices</MudText>
                    <MudList T="string" Dense="true">
                        <MudListItem T="string" Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.Check">
                            <strong>Use a strong master password:</strong> Your password is the only thing protecting your encrypted API keys. Use a unique, strong password or a password manager.
                        </MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem T="string" Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.Check">
                            <strong>Don't share your master password:</strong> There is no password recovery mechanism. If you forget it, you'll need to reset the app.
                        </MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem T="string" Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.Check">
                            <strong>Restrict API keys:</strong> When creating API keys with cloud providers, restrict them to only TTS APIs for minimal attack surface.
                        </MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem T="string" Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.Check">
                            <strong>Review API key permissions:</strong> Follow the principle of least privilege - only grant necessary permissions.
                        </MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem T="string" Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.Check">
                            <strong>Use HTTPS:</strong> Stitch is served over HTTPS, ensuring your communication with TTS APIs is encrypted in transit.
                        </MudListItem>
                        <MudListItem T="string" Icon="@Icons.Material.Filled.Check">
                            <strong>Audit your API usage:</strong> Regularly check your cloud provider dashboards to monitor API usage and detect any anomalies.
                        </MudListItem>
                    </MudList>

                    <MudDivider Class="my-4" />

                    <MudText Typo="Typo.h6" Class="mb-2">üåê What Data Leaves Your Browser?</MudText>
                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-3">
                        To be completely transparent, here's what gets sent to external services:
                    </MudText>
                    <MudList T="string" Dense="true">
